*****

Gist of argument:

                             
 

1

Consider a circle with center E, point G on the circumference C, radius EG of length r and diameter D.

                             
 

2

Place a vertical line tangent to the circle at G.  

                             
 

3

Let Z be the point on the tangent such that the line from Z to center of circle E creates an angle ZEG of 30 deg.  

                             
 

4

Triangle ZEG has a right angle at G and the 30 degree angle at E.

                             
 

5

Consider the top of the triangle to be angle ZEG, so the (unequal) sides are ZE and GE and the base is GZ.

                             
 

6

In right triangle ZGE, designate length ZE as hyp for hypotenuse and length ZG as opp for side opposite central angle ZEG.  The third side length is r.

                             
 

7

Length opp is one-half of the side of a polygon of six sides that circumscribes the circle of radius r.

                             
 

8

By Euclid VI.3, the ratio of hyp to opp is 2:1 (or cosecant of angle ZEG).

                             
 

9

Also, the ratio of r to opp is square root 3: 1 (or cotangent of angle ZEG).

                             
 

10

Note bene: the ratio of opp to r gives the first estimate of C/D as 6*(1:square root 3) and is larger than true C/D.

                             
 

11

To calculate, with square root of 3 estimated as 1.5, so 1/1.5 = 2/3, so 6*2/3 = 12/3 = 4, we get C/D = 4.

                             
                                
 

12

Now, increase the number of sides of the polygon by bisecting the angle ZEG repeatedly, increasing opp/r, bettering C/D.

                             
 

13

As an example, use a circle of radius r (C4-correction was r=153,now r=265/153=1.7) and right triangle ZEG with hyp and opp as the other sides.

                             
 

14

In the example, hyp/opp=2/1=307/153 and r/opp=square root 3/1=265/153, so r/opp is less than hyp/opp as expected for the circumscribed polygon case.

                             
 

15

Note that these two formulas use all three sides of right triangle ZEG and knowing r means all lengths of sides are known.

                             
                                
 

16

To make the first increase in number of sides, bisect angle ZEG.  

                             
 

17

Construct line EH from center E to point H on tangent line.

                             
 

18

Because H is on the tangent line outside the circle and between Z and G, EH > r and EH < hyp from triangle ZEG.

                             
 

19

Let HGE be the new right triangle with right angle HGE and angle HEG = 15 degrees.

                             
 

20

Consider the top of this triangle to be angle HEG, so the (unequal) sides are HE and GE and the base is GH.

                             
 

21

In right triangle HGE, designate length HE as hyp2 and base length GH as opp2 (side opposite top angle HEG).

                             
 

22

As before, the third side has length r.

                             
 

23

Now compare (shorter) base GH in right triangle HGE to base GZ of right triangle ZGE. (C1-corrected)  

                             
 

24

Base GZ is bifurcated by H, giving segments GH and HZ.

                             
 

25

The angle ZEG was bisected into two equal parts, but segments GH and HZ are not equal.

                             
 

26

By Euclid VI:3, for a bisected angle at the top of a triangle, the segments of the base have the same ratio as the lengths of the sides.  

                             
 

27

Because sides ratio ZE to r in triangle ZGE has ZE > r, base segments ratio ZH to HG will have ZH > HG.

                             
                                
 

28

Now use the construction for angle HEG to estimate the polygon side using the new (shorter) right triangle HGE.

                             
 

29

Its base GH is one-half of one side of the 12-sided polygon determined by angle HEG being 15 degrees.

                             
 

30

We know the radius r which is one side of triangle HGE, but we need to know the length of HG. (C2-shortened)

                             
 

31

We seek to express the length HG in terms of the known ratios hyp/opp (or hyp/base) and r/opp (or r/base).

                             
 

32

By Euclid above for the larger right triangle ZGE, unequal sides ratio hyp/r = unequal base segments ratio ZH/HG.

                             
 

33

Now expand the ratio numerator to include both pieces, keeping the denominator the same.

                             
 

34

This gives ratio two sides/r = base/HG which is hyp + r/r = base ZG/base segment HG.

                             
 

35

Next swap two 'middle' components, ie for 1/4=3/12, it is also true that 1/3=4/12, so use that!

                             
 

36

This gives ratio two sides/base = r/HG which is hyp + r/ZG = r/HG.(C3-clearer to write base instead of ZG?)

                             
 

37

We know hyp/ZG and r/ZG from (C5-addition: line 14) the ratios in the example: hyp/ZG=hyp/opp=307/153 and r/ZG=r/opp=265/153.

                             
 

38

That means hyp +r/ZG = hyp/opp + r/opp = (hyp + r)/opp = (307+265)/153 = 571/153.

                             
 

39

Therefore r/HG=571/153, which is larger than the starting ratio r/ZG=265/153.

                             
                                
 

40

Now work to get C/D by flipping the ratio which gives us that the ratio of the tangent segment HG to the radius r is smaller than before.

                             
 

41

This gives us a next approximation for the ratio of the circumference to the diameter as follows.

                             
 

42

The tangent segment HG is one-half the length of a side of a polygon with 12 sides and r is half the diameter D.

                             
 

43

Thus, the second approximation of the ratio of the circumference to the diameter is 12*HG/r.

                             
 

44

HG/r is 153:571, so what is 12*HG/r? It is (1530+307): 571 or 1836:571 or 3 123/571 or 3 1/5 approximately.

                             
 

45

This value is less than the first estimate C/D=4 and greater than the proposition 3 result 3 1/7 for the circumscribed case.

                             
 

46

Then we repeat for more bisections of the angle at E.

Greek numbers used by Archimedes:

 

ϚϜϞϠ

stigma, digamma,koppa,sampi

                           
 

source:http://www.mlahanas.de/Greeks/Counting.htm

                              
 

1=α,2=β,3=γ,4=δ,5=ε,6={digamma,Ϝ , or stigma,Ϛ },7=ζ,8=η,9=θ,10=ι

                              
 

11=ια, ...,20=ϰ, 21=ϰα,..., 30=λ,40=μ,50=ν,60=ξ,70=ο,80=π,90=Ϟ

                              
 

100=ρ,200=σ,300=τ,400=υ,500=φ,600=χ,700=ψ,800=ω,900=Ϡ sampi

                              
 

1000-9999 use iota sub or superscript with letters for 1-9

                              
 

10000=M, and higher numbers put the number in front of M (or on top of it)

                              
 

27 symbols: numbers 1-10, tenths 20-100, hundredths 200-900, greek letters plus 3-4 phoenician symbols

                              
 

11-19: ia, ibeta, etc.; 100-900: 347 tau mu zeta

                              
                                
      

Remember: 10 is iota, 100 is rho; 6, 90 and 900 are special.
